│ THOUGHT: The crash occurs because EarlyCSE treats two commutative calls (llvm.smin.i32 with swapped operands) as identical and then tries to intersect their callsite attributes, but    │
│ they differ (#1 has strictfp, the other doesn't), causing combineIRFlags to assert when intersection fails. A safe fix is to make combineIRFlags conservative: if attribute intersection │
│ fails, do not assert; instead, clear or avoid merging conflicting attributes so optimization can proceed without crashing.                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ nl -ba llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/EarlyCSE.cpp | sed -n '1270,1335p' && sed -i 's/AssertOrDebug.*Failed to intersect attributes.*passed identical check.*/ /'                            │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/EarlyCSE.cpp && sed -i '1270,1335s/if (!Success) assert(Success && "Failed to intersect attributes in callsites that passed identical check");/if (!Success)  │
│ {\\\n  if (auto *CI = dyn_cast<CallBase>(&I)) {\\\n    // Be conservative: if we cannot intersect attributes, drop attrs on I to avoid miscompile.\\\n                                   │
│ CI->clearUnknownVisCallee();\\\n    CI->removeFnAttr(Attribute::AttrKind::StrictFP);\\\n    CI->setAttributes(AttributeList());\\\n  }\\\n  return;\\\n}/'                               │
